---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "What is the difference between a CSS minifier and a JS minifier?",
    answer: "A CSS minifier removes whitespace, comments, and redundant rules from CSS files to reduce file size. A JS minifier does the same for JavaScript but also performs more aggressive transformations: renaming variables to shorter names (mangling), removing dead code, and sometimes inlining small functions. Both minifiers reduce file size to improve page load speed, but JS minification is more complex because it must preserve program behavior across more transformation types."
  },
  {
    question: "How much file size reduction can I expect from minification?",
    answer: "CSS minification typically reduces file size by 20–40%. JavaScript minification — especially with variable mangling and tree shaking — can reduce file size by 50–80% before gzip compression. After gzip or Brotli compression, the difference between minified and unminified files shrinks, but minified files still compress better because repeated short identifiers compress more efficiently than long variable names."
  },
  {
    question: "Should I minify CSS and JS manually or use a build tool?",
    answer: "For production projects, use a build tool (Vite, webpack, Rollup, esbuild) to minify automatically as part of your build pipeline. Manual minification with online tools is useful for quick one-off optimization, debugging a single file, or understanding how minification transforms your code. Build tools also handle source maps, which are essential for debugging minified production code."
  },
  {
    question: "Can minification break CSS or JavaScript?",
    answer: "Poorly written CSS can break under minification if you rely on adjacent-sibling selectors that depend on whitespace, or if you use hacks that depend on comment placement. JavaScript is more fragile — aggressive mangling can break code that uses eval(), relies on Function.name, or accesses properties via string literals that match variable names. Always test minified output in staging before deploying to production."
  },
  {
    question: "Do I still need to minify if I use gzip or Brotli compression?",
    answer: "Yes. Minification and compression are complementary, not alternatives. Compression reduces the size of the data transmitted over the network. Minification reduces the size of the file the browser must parse and execute. A minified + compressed file is smaller than a compressed-only file, and the browser still saves CPU time by parsing a smaller file. Use both for optimal performance."
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="CSS vs JS Minifier: Which to Use? (2025)"
  description="CSS minifier vs JS minifier — understand how each works, how much size reduction to expect, and when to use online tools vs build pipelines. Free minifiers at DevPlaybook."
  faq={faq}
>
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <nav class="text-sm text-text-muted mb-4">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-accent">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2">/</span>
      <a href="/tools" class="hover:text-accent">Tools</a>
      <span class="mx-2">/</span>
      <span>CSS vs JS Minifier</span>
    </nav>

    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-3">CSS vs JS Minifier: Which to Use? (2025)</h1>
    <p class="text-text-muted mb-8 text-lg">Both remove unnecessary bytes from your code, but they work differently and require different care. Here's what you need to know before minifying either.</p>

    <div class="bg-accent/10 border border-accent/20 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8">
      <p class="font-semibold text-white mb-1">Quick Answer</p>
      <p class="text-text-muted text-sm"><strong class="text-white">CSS minifier</strong>: removes whitespace and comments, ~20–40% size reduction. <strong class="text-white">JS minifier</strong>: removes whitespace + renames variables, ~50–80% reduction. Use build tools in production; use online tools for quick one-off optimization. Try <a href="/tools/css-formatter" class="text-accent hover:underline">DevPlaybook's CSS tools</a> for quick formatting and compression.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-8">
      <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-gray-800 text-white">
            <th class="text-left p-3 border border-gray-700">Feature</th>
            <th class="text-left p-3 border border-gray-700">CSS Minifier</th>
            <th class="text-left p-3 border border-gray-700">JS Minifier</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="text-text-muted">
          <tr>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Whitespace removal</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Yes</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Yes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Variable renaming</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">No</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Yes (mangling)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Dead code removal</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Basic</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Advanced (tree shaking)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Typical size reduction</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">20–40%</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">50–80%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700 font-medium text-white">Risk of breaking code</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Low</td>
            <td class="p-3 border border-gray-700">Medium (with mangling)</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">When to Minify CSS</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li>Any CSS file served to end users in production</li>
      <li>Third-party CSS libraries you bundle into your project</li>
      <li>Critical inline CSS in the <code class="text-accent">&lt;head&gt;</code> to reduce above-the-fold render blocking</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">When to Minify JavaScript</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-2 text-sm">
      <li>All JavaScript in production, especially large frameworks and libraries</li>
      <li>Code split bundles and lazy-loaded chunks</li>
      <li>Service workers and web workers where parse time matters</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/50 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8 text-center">
      <p class="text-white font-semibold mb-2">Format or minify CSS in your browser</p>
      <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-4">Free CSS formatter and minifier — no sign-up, no data sent to servers.</p>
      <a href="/tools/css-formatter" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-accent hover:bg-accent/80 text-white font-medium px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg transition-colors">
        Open CSS Formatter →
      </a>
    </div>

    <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />

    <FaqSection faq={faq} title="CSS vs JS Minifier — FAQ" />

    <div class="mt-8 text-sm text-text-muted">
      <p class="font-medium text-white mb-2">Related comparisons</p>
      <ul class="space-y-1">
        <li><a href="/compare/json-formatter-vs-validator" class="text-accent hover:underline">JSON Formatter vs Validator: Which to Use?</a></li>
        <li><a href="/compare/markdown-vs-html-editor" class="text-accent hover:underline">Markdown vs HTML Editor: Which to Use?</a></li>
        <li><a href="/compare/base64-vs-url-encoder" class="text-accent hover:underline">Base64 vs URL Encoder: Which to Use?</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
